TY  - JOUR
AU  - Stoughton, Neal M.
AU  - Wong, Kit Pong
T1  - Option Compensation and Industry Competition
PY  - 2009
Y1  - 2009/01/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfn001
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 13
IS  - 1
SP  - 147
EP  - 180
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - Compensation policy has become one of the most important ingredients of corporate governance. In this paper we take a new look at the issue, by contrasting the use of options with that of stock. We do this by integrating the repricing or resetting aspect of options with that of industrial structure. We show that industry competition may play an important role in dictating which form of compensation is optimal. When aggressive competition for key professional staff is an issue, the flexibility of options may actually become a disadvantage and therefore pure stock compensation may survive as an equilibrium. Thus compensation trends may be partly explained by trends in the nature of the competitive environment.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfn001
ER  - 



